<TITLE> Illegal riverbank structures: HC rejects industrialists' petitions </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 21 (bdnews24.com)  The High Court on Sunday rejected petitions filed by six industrial groups seeking an injunction to stop Narayanganj district administration from dismantling their illegal establishments set up on the bank of the Sitalakhya. The High Court bench of justices Syed Mahmud Hossain and ATM Fazle Kabir rejected the petitions of City Group, Scan Cement, Akiz Group, Molla Salt, Kamal Vegetable and ACI Group However, it ordered the Narayanganj authorities to wait for one month before removing any property owned by the City Group since it had a previous outstanding petition pending in the Appellate Division challenging the validity of the demolition notice itself. The properties of the other five industrial groups can be demolished, the court said. This ruling follows on from a High Court ruling of June 26 last year ordering the government to demolish all illegal structures encroaching on the four rivers surrounding Dhaka citythe Buriganga, Turag, Sitalakhya and Balu. This was followed by another High Court ruling on Jan 24 this year ordering the government to begin demolishing the illegal structures built on the banks of the four rivers by February. In line with the order, on Feb 9 the Narayanganj district authorities sent a notice to the six industrial groups instructing it to remove their illegal structures set up on the bank of Sitalakhya. In the ruling on Sunday, the court criticised Bangladesh Inland Water Transport Corporation (BIWTC) for its role in supporting the establishment of illegal structures by the lessees on the riverside Advocate Manzil Morshed was present at the court on behalf of the rights groups while barristers Rafique-ul-Haque, Rokanuddin Mahmud and Mahmudul Islam stood for the petitioners. bdne
